<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<pretext xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

	<docinfo/>

	<slideshow>
		<title>Getting Started with <pretext/></title>
		<subtitle>Author, Build, and Publish in Two Hours</subtitle>

		<slide label="welcome">
			<title>Welcome</title>

			<p>
				Thanks for being here. Over the next two hours, you will
				author, build, and publish a small lesson using <pretext/> —
				entirely in your web browser.
			</p>

			<p>
				No installs. No command line wizardry. No prior experience required.
			</p>

			<p>
				If you can write a worksheet and you have seen <latex/> once,
				you can write in <pretext/>.
			</p>
		</slide>

		<slide label="who-this-is-for">
			<title>Who This Workshop Is For</title>

			<p pause="no">
				This workshop assumes you are:
			</p>

			<ul pause="no">
				<li>An instructor curious about authoring your own course materials</li>
				<li>New to <pretext/> (and probably new to GitHub too)</li>
				<li>Comfortable editing text and clicking around a browser</li>
			</ul>

			<p>
				You do <em>not</em> need to know Git, XML, the command line,
				or how to install software. We will treat all of that as a
				black box today.
			</p>
		</slide>

		<slide label="the-promise">
			<title>What You Will Leave With</title>

			<p>
				By the end of this session, you will have:
			</p>

			<dl pause="no">
				<li>
					<title>A working authoring setup</title>
					<p>Running in your browser, ready to use again tomorrow.</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<title>A small lesson you wrote yourself</title>
					<p>Built from real <pretext/> source, using structures you will recognize.</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<title>A public web link</title>
					<p>A real URL you can share with colleagues or students.</p>
				</li>
			</dl>

			<p>
				That is the whole goal. Everything else is a bonus.
			</p>
		</slide>

		<slide label="what-is-pretext">
			<title>What Is <pretext/>?</title>

			<p>
				<pretext/> is a free, open-source authoring system for
				textbooks, lecture notes, worksheets, and articles.
			</p>

			<p>
				The key idea: you describe <em>what your content is</em> —
				a definition, an example, an exercise — and <pretext/>
				decides how it should look.
			</p>

			<p>
				One source file. Many polished outputs.
			</p>
		</slide>

		<slide label="write-once">
			<title>Write Once, Publish Everywhere</title>

			<p pause="no">
				From a single <pretext/> source, you can generate:
			</p>

			<ul pause="no">
				<li>An interactive website</li>
				<li>A print-ready PDF</li>
				<li>An ePub for e-readers</li>
				<li>Braille and large-print editions</li>
			</ul>

			<p>
				You write your content once. When tomorrow's format comes along,
				your source is ready for it.
			</p>
		</slide>

		<slide label="why-care">
			<title>Why Instructors Care</title>

			<dl pause="no">
				<li>
					<title>Accessibility by default</title>
					<p>Screen-reader friendly, keyboard navigable, and ready for students who need alternative formats — without extra work from you.</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<title>Your content, your control</title>
					<p>Free, open, and yours to adapt, remix, and share.</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<title>Built for the long run</title>
					<p>Structured source that will still be usable in ten years.</p>
				</li>
			</dl>
		</slide>

		<slide label="latex-bridge">
			<title>If You Know <latex/>, You Have a Head Start</title>

			<p>
				Much of what you already know transfers directly.
			</p>

			<p>
				<line>Inline math: <c>\(x^2\)</c> becomes <c>&lt;m&gt;x^2&lt;/m&gt;</c></line>
				<line>Displayed math: <c>\[ \int f \]</c> becomes <c>&lt;me&gt;\int f&lt;/me&gt;</c></line>
				<line>Sections, lists, examples, theorems: all familiar, just tagged differently</line>
			</p>

			<p>
				The math inside the tags is still <latex/>. You are mostly
				learning a new wrapper, not a new language.
			</p>
		</slide>

		<slide label="today-plan">
			<title>Today's Plan</title>

			<dl pause="no">
				<li>
					<title>First: we get everyone set up</title>
					<p>Launch a workspace in your browser. No installs.</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<title>Next: a quick tour</title>
					<p>Where the source lives, how to build it, how to preview it.</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<title>Then: the main event</title>
					<p>You write a small lesson using a handful of <pretext/> structures.</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<title>Finally: publish and share</title>
					<p>Your lesson goes live on a public URL.</p>
				</li>
			</dl>
		</slide>

		<slide label="how-we-work">
			<title>How We Will Work Together</title>

			<ul pause="no">
				<li>Follow along on your own laptop — this is hands-on, not a lecture</li>
				<li>Use the printed quick reference when you need a reminder</li>
				<li>Ask questions out loud; someone else probably has the same one</li>
				<li>If you get stuck, raise a hand — we will come to you</li>
				<li>If something breaks, that is normal; we have a backup plan</li>
			</ul>

			<p>
				The goal is <em>finished</em>, not <em>perfect</em>.
			</p>
		</slide>

		<slide label="ready">
			<title>Ready?</title>

			<p>
				Open your laptop, open your browser, and make sure you are
				signed in to GitHub.
			</p>

			<p>
				On the next step, we will all launch our workspace together.
			</p>

			<p>
				Let's build something.
			</p>
		</slide>

	</slideshow>
</pretext>
